rm3 = 000000\n|pattern_la3 = _whiteborder\n|rightarm3 = 000000\n|pattern_ra3 = _whiteborder\n|shorts3 = 000000\n|socks3 = 000000\n}}\n\n[[File:Stadio Lino Turina.JPG|thumb|right|Stadio ''Lino Turina'']]\n\n'''Feralpisal\u00f2''' is an [[Football in Italy|Italian association football]] club located in [[Sal\u00f2]], [[Lombardy]], and representing also the nearby town of [[Lonato del Garda]], Lombardy.\n\nThe club currently play in [[Serie C]], the third tier of Italian football.\n\n==History==\nThe club was founded in summer 2009, from the merger between two clubs, both of [[Serie D]]:\n* '''[[A.C. Sal\u00f2]]''' of [[Sal\u00f2]], founded in 1985, as ''A.C. Sal\u00f2 Benaco'' and so renamed since 2001,\n* '''[[A.C. Feralpi Lonato]]''' of [[Lonato del Garda]], founded in 1980, as ''A.C. Lonato'' and so renamed since 1985.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bresciaoggi.it/stories/Sport/59325__feralpi-sal__ununione_gigante/|title=Feralpi-Sal\u00f2, \u00e8 un'unione gigante|first=Edizioni Brescia|last=S.p.A.|publisher=|accessdate=17 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 August 2009 the club was admitted to [[Lega Pro Seconda Divisione]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.feralpisalo.it/stampa09/gbs12ago2009.pdf|title=FERALPISAL\u00d2|website=www.feralpisalo.it|accessdate=17 September 2018}}{{Dead link|date=August 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> in place of not admitted [[U.S. Pistoiese 1921|Pistoiese]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bresciaoggi.it/stories/Home/76166_macalli_il_sal__ripescato_in_seconda_divisione/|title=Bresciaoggi|first=Edizioni Brescia|last=S.p.A.|website=Bresciaoggi.it|accessdate=17 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923194723/http://www.bresciaoggi.it/stories/Home/76166_macalli_il_sal__ripescato_in_seconda_divisione/|archive-date=23 September 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bresciaoggi.it/stories/Sport/77408__feralpi_sal_una_scalata_da_vertigine/|title=Feralpi Sal\u00f2, una scalata da vertigine|first=Edizioni Brescia|last=S.p.A.|publisher=|accessdate=17 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn the season 2010\u201311 from [[Lega Pro Seconda Divisione]] group A,  the club gained  promotion to [[Lega Pro Prima Divisione]] via the playoffs, for the first time ever.\n\n==Colours and badge==\n\nIts colours are [[blue]] and [[green]]: representing ''[[A.C. Sal\u00f2 Valsabbia|Sal\u00f2]]'' and ''[[A.C. Feralpi Lonato|Feralpi Lonato]]''.<ref>http://miticosalo.altervista.org//stampa09/bsoggi13giu2009.pdf</ref>\n\n==Current squad==\n''As of 31 January 2020.''\n\n{{Fs start}}\n{{Fs player | no=  1 | nat= ITA | name= [[Luca Liverani]] |pos=GK}}\n{{Fs player | no=  3 | nat= ITA | name= [[Davide Mordini]]| pos=DF}}\n{{Fs player | no=  4 | nat= ITA | name= [[Nicolas Giani]]| pos=DF}}\n{{Fs player | no=  5 | nat= ITA | name= [[Michele Rinaldi (footballer, born 1987)|Michele Rinaldi]]|pos=DF}}\n{{Fs player | no=  6 | nat= ITA | name=[[Fabio Eguelfi]]|pos=DF|other=<small>on loan from [[Atalanta B.C.|Atalanta]]</small>}}\n{{Fs player | no=  7 | nat= ITA | name= Mattia Tirelli|pos=FW}}\n{{Fs player | no=  8 | nat= ITA | name= Luca Magnino|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player | no=  9 | nat= ITA | name= [[Andrea Caracciolo]]|pos=FW|other=[[Captain (association football)|Captain]]}}\n{{Fs player | no= 10 | nat= ITA | name= [[Tommaso Ceccarelli]] |pos=FW}}\n{{Fs player | no= 11 | nat= ITA | name=[[Luca Miracoli]]|pos=FW|other=<small>on loan from [[Como 1907|Como]]</small>}}\n{{Fs player | no= 12 | nat= ITA | name= Daniele Spezia|pos=GK}}\n{{Fs player | no= 13 | nat= ITA | name= [[Elia Legati]]|pos=DF}}\n{{Fs mid}}\n{{Fs player | no= 14 | nat= ITA | name=[[Davide Vitturini]]|pos=DF}}\n{{Fs player | no= 17 | nat= ITA | name= [[Fabio Scarsella]]|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player | no= 18 | nat= ITA | name= [[Simone Pesce]]|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player | no= 19 | nat= ITA | name= Marco Bertoli|pos=FW}}\n{{Fs player | no= 21 | nat= ITA | name= [[Federico Carraro]]|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player | no= 22 | nat= ITA | name= [[Victor De Lucia]]|pos=GK}}\n{{Fs player | no= 23 | nat= ROU | name= [[Denis Hergheligiu]]|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player | no= 25 | nat= ITA | name= [[Daniele Altobelli]]|pos=MF|other=<small>on loan from [[U.S. Salernitana 1919|Salernitana]]</small>}}\n{{Fs player | no= 27 | nat= ITA | name= [[Luca Guidetti]]|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player | no= 28 | nat= ITA | name= [[Luca Baldassin]]|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player | no= 30 | nat= ITA | name= [[Pasquale Maiorino]]|pos=FW|other=<small>on loan from [[A.S. Livorno Calcio|Livorno]]</small>}}\n{{Fs player | no= 31 | nat= ITA | name= [[Marco Zambelli]]|pos=DF}}\n{{Fs end}}\n\n===Out on loan===\n{{Fs start}}\n{{Fs player | no=  | nat= ITA | name= Giovanni Arrighi|pos=GK|other=at [[A.S.D. Villafranca|Villafranca]]}}\n{{Fs player | no=  | nat= ITA | name= Davide Piazza|pos=DF|other=at Breno}}\n{{Fs player | no=  | nat= ITA | name= Christian Travaglini|pos=DF|other=at [[U.S. Inveruno|Inveruno]]}}\n{{Fs mid}}\n{{Fs player | no=  | nat= ITA | name= [[Alessio Miceli]]|pos=MF|other=at [[Olbia Calcio 1905|Olbia]]}}\n{{Fs player | no=  | nat= ITA | name= Leonardo Moraschi|pos=FW|other=at Breno}}\n{{Fs end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{in lang|it}} [http://www.feralpisalo.it/ Official homepage]\n\n{{Serie C}}\n{{Football in Italy}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2011}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Feralpisalo}}\n[[Category:Football clubs in Italy]]\n[[Category:Association football clubs established in 2009]]\n[[Category:Football clubs in Lombardy]]\n[[Category:Serie C clubs]]\n[[Category:2009 establishments in Italy]]\n\n\n{{Italy-footyclub-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Dawnseeker2000", "label": "safe", "comment": "MOS:DATEUNIFY (audit)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Feralpisal%C3%B2"}
{"title_page": "Ari (name)", "text_new": "{{original research|date=June 2018}}\n'''Ari''' is a given name in many languages and cultures, for both men and women. It also may be a nickname for a wide variety of unrelated names.\n\n==Etymology==\n=== Badaga ===\nAri in the [[Badaga language]], \"Ari\" (\"A:ri\") has a literal meaning of \"sun-like\" and is used as a male name, sometimes changed to \"[[Harry (given name)|Harry]]\" in the case of converts to Christianity.<ref name=\"hockings92\" />\n\n===Finnic languages===\nAri is thought to be a [[Finnic languages|Finnic]] form of [[Adrian]].<ref name=\"balodis09\" />\n\n===German===\nAri in [[German language|German]] is masculine name and means \"[[eagle]]\"<ref name=\"stewart93\" /> or \"great bird\".\n\n=== Greek ===\nAri or [[Aris (disambiguation)|Aris]] is a common shortened version of the [[Greek language|Greek]] names [[Aristotle]], [[Ariadne]], [[Ariana (name)|Ariana]], [[Arietta (disambiguation)|Arietta]], [[Aristides]], [[Aristarchus (disambiguation)|Aristarchus]], [[Aristomenes]], [[Aristobulus (disambiguation)|Aristobulos]], [[Aristoxenos]], [[Aristos (disambiguation)|Aristos]], [[Aristophanes]], [[Aristea]], Aristotelis, and others, the majority of which are compounds of the adjectival superlative ''\u00e1ristos'', \"best\" or \"superior\". They are also modern Greek transliterations for [[Ares]], the god of war and the name for the [[planet Mars]]. The archaic Greek prefix ''ari-''<ref name=\"greek\" /> (e.g. in ''Ariadne'', ''[[Arimnestus]]'' etc.) or ''eri-'', a cognate of ''\u00e1ristos'', means \"very\" or \"verily\".\n\n===Hebrew===\n{{see also | Arieh | Aryeh (name) | Arie}}\nAri is a common masculine given name in [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]] (\u05d0\u05e8\u05d9\u05d4). It means [[lion]].\n\n==People named Ari==\n<!-- ordered by surname -->\n* [[Ari Ahonen]] (born 1981), Finnish ice hockey goaltender\n* [[Ari Angervo]] (born 1944), Finnish classical violinist and conductor\n* [[Ari Anjala]], Finnish orienteering competitor\n* [[Ari Ankorin]] (1908\u20131986), Israeli politician and lawyer\n* [[Ari Babakhanov]], Uzbek musician\n* [[Ari Behn]] (1972\u20132019), Norwegian author and husband of Princess M\u00e4rtha Louise of Norway\n* [[Ari Ben-Menashe]] (born 1952), Iranian-born Israeli businessman, security consultant and author\n* [[Ari Berk]] (born 1967), American writer\n* [[Ari Borovoy]] (born 1979), Mexican musician\n* [[Ari Boyland]] (born 1987), New Zealand actor\n* [[Ari Brown]] (born 1944), American jazz musician\n* [[Ari Brynjolfsson]] (1927\u20132013), Icelandic physicist\n* [[Ari Cohen]], Canadian actor\n* [[Ari Elon]] (born 1950), Israeli writer, Bible scholar, and educator\n* [[Ari Emanuel]] (born 1961), American talent agent\n* [[Ari Fleischer]] (born 1960), former White House Press Secretary for U.S. President George W. Bush\n* [[Ari Folman]] (born 1962), Israeli film director, screenwriter and film score composer\n* [[Ari Freyr Sk\u00falason]] (born 1987), Icelandic footballer\n* [[Ari Gold (filmmaker)]], American filmmaker, actor, musician\n* [[Ari Gold (musician)]] (born 1977), American R&B artist\n* [[Ari Glass]] (born 1989), American painter and artist\n* [[Ari L. Goldman]] (born 1949), American journalist and professor\n* [[Ari Graynor]] (born 1983), American actress\n* [[Ari Greenberg]] (born 1981), American contract bridge player\n* [[Ari Gr\u00f6ndahl]] (born 1989), Finnish ice hockey defenceman\n* [[Ari Haanp\u00e4\u00e4]] (born 1965), Finnish ice hockey player\n* [[Ari Herstand]] (born 1985), American singer/songwriter\n* [[Ari Hest]] (born 1979), American singer-songwriter\n* [[Ari Hjelm]] (born 1962), Finnish football coach and former player\n* [[Ari Hoenig]] (born 1973), American jazz drummer, composer and educator\n* [[Ari Hoogenboom]] (1927\u20132014), American historian\n* [[Ari Hoptman]] (born 1967), American actor and playwright\n* [[Ari Huumonen]] (1956\u20132013), Finnish discus thrower\n*{{Nihongo|[[Ari Ichihashi]]|\u5e02\u6a4b \u6709\u91cc||born 1977}}, Japanese long-distance runner\n* [[Ari Jabotinsky]] (1910\u20131969), Revisionist Zionist activist, Israeli politician and academic\n* [[Ari Joshua]], American guitarist, songwriter, member of the band Big High\n* [[Ari J\u00f3nsson]] (born 1994), Faroese footballer\n* [[Ari J\u00f3sefsson]] (1939\u20131964), Icelandic poet\n* [[Ari Kattainen]] (born 1958), Finnish orienteering competitor\n* [[Ari Kelman]], American historian and professor\n* [[Ari Koivunen]] (born 1984), Finnish heavy metal singer\n* [[Ari Kurniawan]] (born 1978), Indonesian footballer\n* [[Ari Laptev]] (born 1950), Russian mathematician\n* [[Ari Lasso]] (born 1973), Indonesian musician\n* [[Ari Lehman]] (born 1965), American actor and performance artist\n* [[Ari Lemmke]] (born 1963), Finnish computer programmer\n*[[Lauv|Ari Leff]] (born 1994), American singer and songwriter\n* [[Ari Libsker]] (born 1972), Israeli filmmaker and journalist\n* [[Ari Lohenoja]] (born 1958), Finnish television producer and director\n* [[Ari Mannio]] (born 1987), Finnish javelin thrower\n* [[Ari Marcopoulos]] (born 1957), Dutch-American photographer and filmmaker\n* [[Ari Marmell]] (born 1974) American novelist and game writer\n* [[Ari Melber]] (born 1980), American journalist\n* [[Ari Meyers]] (born 1969), American actress\n* [[Ari Millen]] (born 1982), Canadian actor\n* [[Ari Ne'eman]] (born 1987), American autism rights activist\n* [[Ari Nyman]] (born 1984), Finnish footballer\n* [[Aristotle Onassis]] (1906\u20131975), Greek shipping magnate and husband of Jacqueline Kennedy\n* [[Ari Pakarinen]] (born 1969), Finnish javelin thrower\n* [[Ari Palolahti]] (born 1968), Finnish cross-country skier\n* [[Ari Porth]] (born 1970), American attorney, jurist, and politician\n* [[Ari Poutiainen]] (born 1972), Finnish jazz musician and composer\n* [[Ari Puheloinen]] (born 1951), Finnish general\n* [[Ari Pulkkinen]] (born 1982), Finnish video game composer, musician, and sound designer\n* [[Ari Rath]] (1925\u20132017), Austrian-Israeli journalist and writer\n* [[Ari Romero]] (1951\u20132013), Mexican professional wrestler\n* [[Ari Roth]] (born 1961), American theatrical producer, playwright, director, and educator\n* [[Ari Saarinen]] (born 1967), Finnish ice hockey player\n* [[Ari Salin]] (born 1947), Finnish hurdler and sprinter\n* [[Ari Sandel]] (born 1974), American filmmaker\n* [[Ari Santos]] (born 1982), Brazilian futsal player\n* [[Ari Schwartz]], American Internet Policy Advisor\n* [[Ari Shaffir]] (born 1974), American stand-up comedian\n* [[Ari Shapiro]] (born 1978), American radio journalist\n* [[Ari Daniel Shapiro]], American science journalist\n* [[Ari Singh II]], (1724\u20131773), Maharana of Mewar Kingdom\n* [[Ari Sitas]] (born 1952), South African sociologist, writer, dramatist and civic activist\n* [[Ari Suhonen]] (born 1965), Finnish middle distance runner\n* [[Ari Sulander]] (born 1969), Finnish ice hockey goaltender\n* [[Ari Taub (director)]] (born 1965), American filmmaker\n* [[Ari Taub (wrestler)]] (born 1971), Canadian Greco-Roman wrestler\n* [[Ari Telch]] (born 1962), Mexican actor\n* [[Ari \u00deorgilsson]] (1067\u20131148), Icelandic medieval chronicler\n* [[Ari Up]] (1962\u20132010), German-born singer\n* [[Ari V\u00e4\u00e4n\u00e4nen]] (born 1947), Finnish long jumper\n* [[Ari Valvee]] (born 1960), Finnish footballer\n* [[Ari Vatanen]] (born 1952), Finnish politician and former rally driver\n* [[Ari Wallach]] (born 1974), Mexican-American businessman\n* [[Ari Wolfe]] (born 1971), American play-by-play announcer, reporter and anchor\n\n===Fictional characters===\n* Ari Ben Canaan, protagonist in the novel [[Exodus (Uris novel)|''Exodus'']] by Leon Uris and the 1960 film adaptation, played by Paul Newman\n* [[Ari Gold (Entourage)]], on the comedy-drama television series ''Entourage''\n* Ari Tenenbaum, character in  [[Wes Anderson|''Wes Anderson's'']] 2001 movie [[The Royal Tenenbaums]]\n* [[List of Nikita characters#Ari Tasarov|Ari Tasarov]], from the TV series ''[[Nikita (TV series)|Nikita]]''\n* Ari Levinson, [[The Red Sea Diving Resort]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[Ari (disambiguation)|Ari]], for other uses\n*[[Arie]], a Dutch and Hebrew masculine name\n*[[Arieh (disambiguation)]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"balodis09\">{{cite conference |url=http://pi.library.yorku.ca/dspace/bitstream/handle/10315/3615/icos23_105.pdf?sequence=1 |title=Personal Names of Livonian Origin in Latvia: Past and Present |first=Pauls |last=Balodis |date=August 2009 |conference=23rd International Congress of Onomastic Sciences |format=PDF |conferenceurl=http://pi.library.yorku.ca/dspace/handle/10315/2901 |editor=Wolfgang Ahrens |editor2=Sheila Embleton |editor3=Andr\u00e9 Lapierre |isbn=978-1-55014-521-2 |booktitle=Proceedings of the 23rd International Congress of Onomastic Sciences |publisher=[[York University]] |location=Toronto, Canada |pages=105&ndash;116 |accessdate=23 April 2011}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"greek\">{{cite web |last1=Liddell |first1=Henry George |last2=Scott |first2=Robert |title=A Greek-English Lexicon, \u1f00\u03c1\u03b9^- |url=http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0057%3Aentry%3Da%29ri^ |website=Perseus Digital Library}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"hockings92\">{{Citation |last1=Hockings |first1=Paul |last2=Pilot-Raichoor|first2=Christiane |editor=Werner Winter |editor2=Richard A. Rhodes |year=1992 |title=A Badaga-English Dictionary |series=Trends in Linguistics: Documentation |volume=8 |publisher=[[Mouton de Gruyter]] |page=47 |oclc=25963917 |isbn=978-3-11-012677-8 |accessdate=13 Dec 2011 |publication-place=Berlin, Germany |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=a74HA_RX3rIC&lpg=PA47&dq=Ari%20male%20name&pg=PA47#v=onepage&q=Ari%20male%20name&f=false}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"stewart93\">{{Citation |last=Stewart |first=Julia |year=1993 |title=African Names |chapter=A |type=GoogleBook |publisher=[[Kensington Publishing]] |publication-place=New York, New York |page=14 |oclc