ogo                 = \n| founded              =  [[2009 Rugby League Four Nations|2009]]\n| number of teams      = 4\n| region               = International ([[RLIF]])\n| related comps        = [[Rugby League World Cup|World Cup]]\n| current champions    = {{rl|AUS}} (3rd title)\n| most successful team = {{fb|AUS}} (3 titles)\n| website              = \n| current              = [[2016 Rugby League Four Nations|2016]]\n}}\n{{Infobox\n|image1 =\n|caption1 = \n|bodyclass = hlist nowraplinks\n|headerstyle = border-top: 1px solid #aaa\n|header1 = Tournaments\n|data2 = \n*  [[2009 Rugby League Four Nations|2009]]\n*   [[2010 Rugby League Four Nations|2010]]\n*   [[2011 Rugby League Four Nations|2011]]\n*  [[2014 Rugby League Four Nations|2014]]\n*  [[2016 Rugby League Four Nations|2016]]\n}}\n\nThe '''Rugby League Four Nations''', known as the '''Ladbrokes Four Nations''' for sponsorship, is a biennial [[rugby league]] football tournament run in partnership between the [[Australian Rugby League Commission]], [[Rugby Football League]] and [[New Zealand Rugby League]] representing the top three nations in the sport: [[Australia national rugby league team|Australia]], [[England national rugby league team|England]] and [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]].<ref name=\"news1\">{{cite web |url= http://www.news.com.au/couriermail/sport/nrl/story/0,26746,25096474-5003409,00.html|publisher= news.com.au|title= UK stuff-up in league of its own |author=Dean Ritchie |date=2009-02-24|accessdate=2009-04-17}}</ref> The tournament replaced the previous [[Rugby League Tri-Nations|Tri-Nations]] format by including a fourth nation that qualifies by winning their respective regional competition in a rotation between Europe and the South Pacific.  [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Fran\u00e7aise de Rugby \u00e0 XIII|France]] accepted an invitation to play in the inaugural tournament in 2009.<ref name=\"news1\"/>  The tournament is sponsored by [[Ladbrokes]] and therefore officially known as the '''Ladbrokes Four Nations'''.<ref name=\"sl14Nspon\">{{cite web |url= http://www.sportinglife.com/rugbyleague/news/story_get.cgi?STORY_NAME=rleague/09/07/12/RUGBYL_Four_Nations.html|publisher= Sporting Life|title=Gillette to sponsor Four Nations|author=PA|date=2009-07-12|accessdate=2009-07-13}}</ref> No tournament was contested in 2012 to allow teams to prepare for the [[2013 Rugby League World Cup]].<ref name=\"nrl1\">{{cite web |url= http://nrl.com/News/Latest/tabid/10244/default.aspx?id=53525|publisher= NRL Partnership|title= RLIF unveils expanded Test schedule |author=NRL |date=2008-11-22|accessdate=2009-04-17}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===2006\u20132008: Origins===\n{{See also|Rugby League Tri-Nations}}\nThe Four Nations replaced the Tri-Nations tournament that was contested between Australia, New Zealand and Great Britain. The competition ceased in 2006 with the [[RLIF]] wanting more nations to play in regular tournaments with the 'Big Three'. England replaced Great Britain as the third nation and the fourth nation has to qualify, depending on where the tournament is being played the fourth nation is either from the Northern or Southern Hemisphere.\n\n===2009\u20132013: First competitions===\nThe inaugural Four Nations was played in England and France in 2009 with France qualifying to be the fourth nation via winning the [[2005 European Nations Cup|2005 European Championship]]. The big three dominated the tournament with Australia beating England in the final. The next tournament was played the following year in 2010 with Australia and New Zealand hosting the tournament. PNG qualified as the fourth nation through the [[Pacific Cup|2009 Pacific Cup]]. The big three again dominated and Australia beat New Zealand in the final for their third title. 2011 was the third consecutive tournament being held in England and Wales, Wales qualified by winning the [[2010 European Cup|2010 European Championship]]. The final was a repeat of 2009 with Australia beating England. The tournament was not played in 2012 to give teams a rest before the [[2013 Rugby League World Cup|2013 World Cup]].\n\n===2014\u2013: Regular competition===\nThe next Four Nations was played in 2014 after the World Cup. The competition was played in the Southern Hemisphere for the first time since 2010 with Samoa qualifying as the fourth nation. Samoa impressed, although they did not win a game they had close games against the big three. New Zealand beat Australia in the final.\n\nThe next tournament took place in England in 2016. Scotland qualified for the tournament and also became the first qualifying nation to avoid losing every game when they drew with New Zealand 18-all. The final for the 2016 tournament took place at [[Anfield Stadium]] in [[Liverpool]];  after every prior Four Nations final in England had been held at [[Elland Road]], [[Leeds]], and was won by Australia against New Zealand.\n\n==Format==\n===Qualification===\nThe fourth nation alternates between Europe and the Pacific and to date each tournament has seen a different team take part.  [[Rugby League European Cup]] decides the qualifier from Europe and the [[Pacific Rugby League International]] decides the qualifier from the Pacific.\n\nIn 2009 a qualifying tournament was held, the [[Pacific Cup]], involving [[Papua New Guinea national rugby league team|Papua New Guinea]], [[Samoa national rugby league team|Samoa]], [[Tonga national rugby league team|Tonga]], [[Fiji national rugby league team|Fiji]] and the [[Cook Islands national rugby league team|Cook Islands]]. The winners, [[Papua New Guinea national rugby league team|Papua New Guinea]], qualified for the 2010 Four Nations. Likewise in 2010, the [[European Nations Cup (rugby league)|European Nations Cup]] decided the fourth participant in the 2011 tournament, Wales.<ref name=\"nrl1\"/> In 2014, a single game was staged to decide the fourth team for that year with [[Samoa national rugby league team|Samoa]] beating [[Fiji national rugby league team|Fiji]] 32-16. That same year, it was announced that the winner of the [[2014 European Cup (rugby league)|2014 European Cup]] would qualify for the 2016 Four Nations, the winning team being [[Scotland national rugby league team|Scotland]] who qualified on points difference by just 3 points over [[France national rugby league team|France]].\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Year !! Competition !! Qualifier\n|-\n| [[2009 Four Nations|2009]] || [[2005 European Nations Cup]] || {{rl|France}}\n|-\n| [[2010 Four Nations|2010]] || [[Pacific Cup|2009 Pacific Cup]] || {{rl|PNG}}\n|-\n| [[2011 Four Nations|2011]] || [[2010 European Cup|2010 European Nations Cup]] || {{rl|WAL}}\n|- \n| [[2014 Rugby League Four Nations|2014]] || [[Pacific Rugby League International#2014 test|2014 Pacific Qualifier]] || {{rl|SAM}}\n|-\n| [[2016 Rugby League Four Nations|2016]] || [[2014 European Cup|2014 European Nations Cup]] || {{rl|SCO}}\n|}\n\n===Competition===\nThe tournament is organised in round-robin format. Each team plays the others once, before the top two teams play each other in a tournament final. The top two teams are calculated using a league table. Teams receive:\n\n*2 points for a win\n*1 point for a draw\n*0 points for a loss\n\nFor and against then separates teams on equal points.\n\n==Results==\n\nTo date no fourth nation has appeared in the final of the Four Nations and no team from outside of Oceania has won the tournament despite [[England national rugby league team|England]] appearing in two finals, losing both to [[Australia national rugby league team|Australia]].  Furthermore, no fourth nation has even won a single game however [[Scotland national rugby league team|Scotland]] managed to draw 18-18 against [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]] in 2016. [[Samoa national rugby league team|Samoa]] came close to a win in 2014 losing their first two games by just one try.\n\nThe largest winning margin in a game was in 2010 when [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]] beat [[Papua New Guinea national rugby league team|Papua New Guinea]] by 76-12, a margin of 64 points.  There has only been two draws in the history of the tournament when [[Australia national rugby league team|Australia]] and [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]] fought out a 20-20 draw in the 2009 tournament and again a draw when New Zealand played Scotland in the 2016 tournament with an 18-18 draw.\n\n===Tournaments===\n{{Main|Rugby League Four Nations Final}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;width:100%; font-size:90%;\"\n|-\n!width=5%|Year\n!width=10%|Host(s)\n!rowspan=\"22\" style=\"width:1%;background:#fff\"|\n!width=14%|Champions\n!width=7%|Final score\n!width=14%|Runner-up\n!rowspan=\"22\" style=\"width:1%;background:#fff\"|\n!width=7%|Fourth nation\n|-\n|[[2009 Rugby League Four Nations|2009]]\n|align=left|{{ENG}}<br/>{{FRA}}\n|'''{{rl-big|Australia}}'''\n|46 &ndash; 16\n|{{rl-big|England}}\n|{{rl-big|France}}\n|-style=\"background:#D0E6FF\"\n|[[2010 Rugby League Four Nations|2010]]\n|align=left|{{AUS}}<br/>{{NZL}}\n|'''{{rl-big|New Zealand}}'''\n|16 &ndash; 12\n|{{rl-big|Australia}}\n|{{rl-big|PNG}}\n|-\n|[[2011 Rugby League Four Nations|2011]]\n|align=left|{{ENG}}<br/>{{WAL}}\n|'''{{rl-big|Australia}}'''\n|30 &ndash; 8\n|{{rl-big|England}}\n|{{rl-big|Wales}}\n|-style=\"background:#D0E6FF\"\n|[[2014 Rugby League Four Nations|2014]]\n|align=left|{{AUS}}<br/>{{NZL}}\n|'''{{rl-big|New Zealand}}'''\n|22 &ndash; 18\n|{{rl-big|Australia}}\n|{{rl-big|SAM}}\n|-\n|[[2016 Rugby League Four Nations|2016]]\n|align=left|{{ENG}}\n|'''{{rl-big|Australia}}'''\n|34 &ndash; 8\n|{{rl-big|New Zealand}}\n|{{rl-big|SCO}}\n|}\n\n===Standings===\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n{{2009 Rugby League Four Nations Ladder}}\n{{2010 Rugby League Four Nations Ladder}}\n{{2011 Rugby League Four Nations Ladder}}\n{{col-2}}\n{{2014 Rugby League Four Nations Ladder}}\n{{2016 Rugby League Four Nations Ladder}}\n{{col-end}}\n\n===Nation Results===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:left;\"\n|-rank\n!Country\n!Appearances\n!Champions\n!Runners-up\n|-\n|align=left|{{rl|AUS}}||5|| 3 ([[2009 Rugby League Four Nations|2009]], [[2011 Rugby League Four Nations|2011]], [[2016 Rugby League Four Nations|2016]]) || 2 ([[2010 Rugby League Four Nations|2010]], [[2014 Rugby League Four Nations|2014]])\n|-\n|align=left|{{rl|NZL}}||5|| 2 ([[2010 Rugby League Four Nations|2010]], [[2014 Rugby League Four Nations|2014]]) || 1 ([[2016 Rugby League Four Nations|2016]])\n|-\n|align=left|{{rl|ENG}}||5|| 0 || 2 ([[2009 Rugby League Four Nations|2009]], [[2011 Rugby League Four Nations|2011]])\n|-\n|align=left|{{rl|FRA}}||1|| 0 || 0\n|-\n|align=left|{{rl|PNG}}||1|| 0 || 0\n|-\n|align=left|{{rl|SAM}}||1|| 0 || 0\n|-\n|align=left|{{rl|WAL}}||1|| 0 || 0\n|-\n|align=left|{{rl|SCO}}||1|| 0 || 0 \n|}\n\n==Sponsorship==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;margin-left:1em;float:center\"\n!Period\n!Sponsor\n!Name\n|-\n|2009\u201314\n|[[Gillette (brand)|Gillette]]\n|'''Gillette Four Nations'''\n|-\n|2016\u2013\n|[[Ladbrokes]]\n|'''Ladbrokes Four Nations'''\n|}\n\n==Attendances==\n(as of 20 November 2016)\n\n===Average Attendances===\nThe average attendances of the Four Nations tournaments fluctuate between the northern and southern hemisphere competitions with the southern hemisphere always having higher averages than the previous tournaments in the northern hemisphere.  The largest change between two tournaments was between 2009 and 2010 which saw an 18.45% increase or an average of 3,060.  The largest total stadium capacity was 214,500 in 2010 despite this tournament having the lowest stadium occupancy with 64.10%.\n \n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Host !! Total attendance !! Matches !! Average attendance !! % of change !! Stadium Capacity !! % Capacity\n|-\n| [[2009 Rugby League Four Nations|2009]] || {{ENG}}<br>{{FRA}} || 116,089 || 7 || 16,584 || N/A || 159,300 || 72.97%\n|-\n| [[2010 Rugby League Four Nations|2010]] || {{AUS}}<br>{{NZL}} || 137,504 || 7 || 19,644 || {{increase}} 18.45% || 214,500 || 64.10%\n|-\n| [[2011 Rugby League Four Nations|2011]] || {{ENG}}<br>{{WAL}}|| 128,065 || 7 || 18,295 ||  {{decrease}} 6.86% || 193,100 || 66.32%\n|-\n| [[2014 Rugby League Four Nations|2014]] ||{{AUS}}<br>{{NZL}} || 144,722 || 7 || 20,675 ||  {{increase}} 13.00% || 201,400 || 71.85%\n|-\n| [[2016 Rugby League Four Nations|2016]] || {{ENG}} || 132,655 || 7 || 18,951 || {{decrease}} 8.33% || 193,300 || 68.62%\n|-\n|}\n\n===Highest Attendances===\nTo date, there has been 4 attendances over 40,000 and 8 attendances over 30,000.  Three of these attendances were double-headers which took place at [[Eden Park]], [[Auckland]] in 2010, [[Wembley Stadium]], [[London]] in 2011 and [[Suncorp Stadium]], [[Brisbane]] in 2014; the latter two double-headers are also the largest attendances in the respective hemispheres.  Four of these games were tournament finals in 2009, 2010, 2011 and 2016.  Only one final did not have an attendance over 30,000, this being the 2014 edition.    \n  \n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Rank !! Game !! Stadium !! Attendance !! Event \n|-\n| 1 || {{rl|England}} v {{rl|Samoa}}<br/>{{rl|Australia}} v {{rl|New Zealand}} || [[Suncorp Stadium]], [[Brisbane]], [[Australia]]<br>(double-header) || 47,813 || 2014\n|-\n| 2 || {{rl|Australia}} v {{rl|New Zealand}}<br/>{{rl|England}} v {{rl|Papua New Guinea}} || [[Eden Park]], [[Auckland]], [[New Zealand]]<br>(double-header) || 44,324 || 2010\n|-\n| 3 || {{rl|Wales}} v {{rl|New Zealand}}<br/>{{rl|England}} v {{rl|Australia}} || [[Wembley Stadium]], [[London]], [[England]]<br>(double-header)|| 42,344 || 2011\n|-\n| 4 || {{rl|Australia}} v {{rl|New Zealand}} (final) || [[Anfield]], [[Liverpool]], [[England]] || 40,042 || 2016\n|-\n| 5 || {{rl|Australia}} v {{rl|New Zealand}} (final) || [[Suncorp Stadium]], [[Brisbane]], [[Australia]] || 36,299 || 2010\n|-\n|}\n\n===Venues===\nAs of 2016 Four Nations (<small>''in order of matches played and highest attendance''</small>).\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- bgcolor=#bdb76b\n! Stadium !! City !! Matches played !! Highest Attendance\n|-\n|[[Lang Park]] || [[Brisbane]] || 3 || 47,813\n|-\n|[[Eden Park]] || [[Auckland]] || 2 || 44,324\n|-\n|[[Wembley Stadium]] || [[London]] || 2 || 42,344\n|-\n|[[Elland Road]] || [[Leeds]] || 2 || 34,174\n|-\n|[[Westpac Stadium]] || [[Wellington]] || 2 || 25,093\n|-\n|[[Galpharm Stadium]] || [[Huddersfield]] || 2 || 24,070\n|-\n|[[AAMI Park]] || [[Melbourne]] || 2 || 20,585\n|-\n|[[Olympic Stadium (London)|London Stadium]] || [[London]] || 1 || 35,569\n|-\n|[[KC Stadium]] || [[Kingston-upon-Hull|Hull]] || 1 || 23,447\n|-\n|[[DW Stadium]] || [[Wigan]] || 1 || 23,122\n|-\n|[[Ricoh Arena]] || [[Coventry]] || 1 || 21,009\n|-\n|[[WIN Stadium]] || [[Wollongong]] || 1 || 18,456\n|-\n|[[Toll Stadium]] || [[Whangarei]] || 1 || 16,912\n|-\n|[[Forsyth Barr Stadium]] || [[Dunedin]] || 1 || 15,863\n|-\n|[[Halliwell Jones Stadium]] || [[Warrington]] || 1 || 12,491\n|-\n|[[Stade Ernest-Wallon]] || [[Toulouse]] || 1 || 12,412\n|-\n|[[Twickenham Stoop]] || [[London]] || 1 || 12,360\n|-\n|[[Keepmoat Stadium]] || [[Doncaster]] || 1 || 11,529\n|-\n|[[Parramatta Stadium]] || [[Sydney]] || 1 || 11,308\n|-\n|[[Leigh Sports Village]] || [[Leigh, Greater Manchester|Leigh]] || 1 || 10,377\n|-\n|[[Derwent Park]] || [[Workington]] || 1 || 6,628\n|-\n|[[Stade S\u00e9bastien Charl\u00e9ty]] || [[Paris]] || 1 || 6,234\n|-\n|[[Rotorua International Stadium]] || [[Rotorua]] || 1 || 6,000\n|-\n|[[KC Lightstream Stadium]] || [[Kingston upon Hull]] || 1 || 5,337\n|-\n|[[Racecourse Ground]] || [[Wrexham]] || 1 || 5,233\n|}\n\n==Player statistics==\n(As of 2016 Four Nations)\n\n===Overall try-scorers===\n\nOver the history of the competition 125 players have scored tries.  The top try-scorers are [[Jason Nightingale]] of [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]] and [[Ryan Hall (rugby league)|Ryan Hall]] of [[England national rugby league team|England]] with 11 tries each.  The highest try-scorer from a 'fourth nation' is [[Daniel Vidot]] from [[Samoa national rugby league team|Samoa]] who scored 3 tries in the 2014 competition.  [[Australia national rugby league team|Australia]] has had the most try-scorers with 39 different players scoring.  Both Samoa and [[Scotland national rugby league team|Scotland]] have had 8 try-scorers each, making them the 'fourth nations' with the most players scoring.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- bgcolor=#bdb76b\n!Tries scored!!Name\n|-\n|11||[[Jason Nightingale]] (New Zealand), [[Ryan Hall (rugby league)|Ryan Hall]] (England) \n|-\n|10||[[Greg Inglis]] (Australia)\n|-\n|9||[[Brett Morris]] (Australia), [[Cooper Cronk]] (Australia)\n|-\n|8||[[Billy Slater]] (Australia)\n|-\n|7||\n|-\n|6||[[Sam Tomkins]] (England), [[Sam Perrett]] (New Zealand), [[Junior Sa'u]] (New Zealand)\n|-\n|5||[[Michael Jennings (rugby league)|Michael Jennings]] (Australia), [[Lance Hohaia]] (New Zealand), [[Darius Boyd]] (Australia), [[Johnathan Thurston]] (Australia) \n|-\n|4||[[Luke Lewis]] (Australia), [[Cameron Smith]] (Australia), [[Brent Tate]] (Australia), [[Sam Burgess]] (England), [[Tony Clubb]] (England), [[Shaun Kenny-Dowall]] (New Zealand), [[Blake Ferguson]] (Australia), [[Josh Dugan]] (Australia), [[Gerard Beale]] (New Zealand) \n|-\n|3||[[Darren Lockyer]] (Australia), [[Josh Morris (rugby league)|Josh Morris]] (Australia), [[Willie Tonga]] (Australia), [[Peter Fox (rugby league, born 1984)|Peter Fox]] (England), [[Luke Robinson (rugby league)|Luke Robinson]] (England), [[Sika Manu]] (New Zealand), [[Manu Vatuvei]] (New Zealand), [[Daniel Vidot]] (Samoa), [[Gareth Widdop]] (England), [[Jermaine McGillvary]] (England), [[Shaun Johnson]] (New Zealand), [[Jordan Rapana]] (New Zealand), [[Josh Mansour]] (Australia)\n|-\n|2|| [[Daly Cherry-Evans]] (Australia), [[Ben Hunt (rugby league)|Ben Hunt]] (Australia), [[Chris Lawrence (rugby league)|Chri